04313nam a22006135i 9780231553230DE-B159720230529094047.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230529t20232023nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802315532307 a10.7312/chat199662doi  a(DE-B1597)653710  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aKF390.W6bC43 2023 7aHIS0360402bisacsh04a342.7308/78223/eng/202301051 aChatfield, Sara, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aIn Her Own Name :bThe Politics of Women’s Rights Before Suffrage /cSara Chatfield. 1aNew York, NY : bColumbia University Press, c[2023] 4c©2023  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction -- tCHAPTER ONE Life Under Coverture and How It Changed -- tCHAPTER TWO Married Women’s Rights Reforms in American Political Development -- tCHAPTER THREE Social Movements and State Power Reform in State Legislatures -- tCHAPTER FOUR Constitutional Conventions as Key Reform Moments -- tCHAPTER FIVE Decentralized Reform and Policy Diffusion -- tCHAPTER SIX Courts as Collaborators and Catalysts -- tConclusion -- tMethods Appendix -- tAcknowledgments -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aLong before American women had the right to vote, states dramatically transformed their status as economic citizens. In the early nineteenth century, a married woman had hardly any legal existence apart from her husband. By the twentieth, state-level statutes, constitutional provisions, and court rulings had granted married women a host of protections relating to ownership and control of property. Why did powerful men extend these rights during a period when women had so little political sway?In Her Own Name explores the origins and consequences of laws guaranteeing married women’s property rights, focusing on the people and institutions that shaped them. Sara Chatfield demonstrates that the motives of male elites included personal interests, benefits to the larger economy, and bolstering state power. She shows that married women’s property rights could serve varied political goals across regions and eras, from temperance to debt relief to settlement of the West. State legislatures, constitutional conventions, and courts expanded these rights incrementally, and laws spread across the country without national-level coordination.Chatfield emphasizes that the reform of married women’s economic rights rested on exclusionary foundations, including protecting slavery and encouraging settler colonialism. Although some women benefited from property reforms, many others saw their rights stripped away by the same processes. Drawing on a mix of qualitative and quantitative evidence, In Her Own Name sheds new light on the place of women in the fitful democratization of the United States.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aMarried womenxLegal status, laws, etc.zUnited StatesxHistory. 0aWomenxSuffragezUnited StatesxHistory. 0aWomen's rightszUnited StatesxHistory. 7aHISTORY / United States / 19th Century.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.7312/chat1996640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780231553230423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780231553230/original  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK